Finally, in BBC-DB, HybEA achieves an almost perfect H@1 score (99.6%), followed by BERT-INT (92.5%). The other baseline methods fall far behind, with all of them struggling to achieve even a 50% H@1. This large gap can be attributed to the high levels of heterogeneity that were presented in Table 1, with this dataset exhibiting the biggest differences in the statistics of its two constituent KGs.

Overall, we compare HybEA to 5 state-of-the-art EA methods. Three of them (Knowformer, RREA and PipEA) are structure-based methods and the other twp (BERT-INT and COTSAE) are joint approaches. As presented in related works, structure-based approaches generally do not use side information such as entity names. Table 2 presents the effectiveness results of our method, along with the baselines, in all datasets. We observe that HybEA significantly outperforms all baseline methods in all datasets, yielding 90+% scores in all datasets and for all measures. In almost all cases, the runner-up method (underlined in Table 2) is a variation of HybEA.

Another very important observation comes up from the comparison of the H@1 results shown in the HybEA and HybEA (struct. first) rows of Table 2 and the Recall results (since Precision is always 1.0) shown in the factual first and structural first parts of Table 3, respectively. We notice that the vast majority of matches identified by HybEA come from the reciprocity filter and only a very small number of matches are left to be decided by the ranking of the most likely matches returned by the last component.

Despite the above findings, i.e., that the effectiveness of the reciprocity filter alone (Table 3) is higher when the structural model is executed first, we observe that when put as part of the whole pipeline (Table 2), it is more beneficial to execute the factual model first, in all datasets. This means that the reciprocity filter enables to better train both models, when they have a more balanced contribution.

We conduct an ablation study in which we change one single aspect from our pipeline each time, and show that the entire performance drops. This signifies that every single architectural feature has a positive impact in the effectiveness of HybEA. The results of the ablation study are incorporated into Table 2.

Reverse order of components. We experiment with different orders of execution for the structural and factual components, as presented in the last two rows of Table 2. We observe that we get quite different results, with a clear winner, in all datasets, being running the factual component first. In most cases, running the structural component first yields the runner-up approach, at least in terms of H@1. Consequently, we propose running the factual component first as our default configuration.

For evaluating the computational cost of HybEA, we report the FLOPS of each component model in Table 4. On one hand, our structural component is much more computationally expensive than our factual component, while being the most effective one according to Table 2. There is thus a clear trade-off here between computational cost and effectiveness. On the other hand, our factual component allows a high gain in effectiveness for a relatively small computational cost. What could seem surprising is the longer training time of our factual component compared to our structural component. Entity initialization is easy to change, but it can make a big difference. We have shown that in Table 2, when comparing two seemingly similar models, i.e., Knowformer vs HybEA (w/o fact.), whose main difference is random vs Sentence-BERT initialization. Although we do not report more findings here, we have observed that even Sentence-BERT vs BERT or other entity initializations bring quite different results.

In Tables 2 and 3 we have shown that order matters. Despite the fact that the effectiveness of the reciprocity filter alone is higher when the structural component is executed first, in the whole pipeline it is more beneficial to execute the factual component first, in all datasets. Moreover, using the factual component alone yields bad results, compared to employing the structural component alone.

From Tables 2 and 4, we observe that our structural component is the most computationally expensive and the most effective. On the other hand, our factual component brings a high gain in performance for a relatively small computational cost.

Reciprocity Filter.
For a more detailed evaluation, we also present the precision (Pr), recall (Re), and F1-score (F1) of the entity pairs added to the final results by the reciprocity filter of each component, in Table 3. We compute those measures cumulatively for the pairs suggested by each component over all cycles. More detailed results, per cycle, not listed here for presentation purposes, show, as expected, that the vast majority of pairs suggested by the reciprocity filter are provided in the first cycle. Overall, we can say that the reciprocity filter is highly effective, yielding perfect precision and very high recall.

It is essential to note here that the order of the components is determining the results of Table 3, as the second component is only called for the pairs that the first component could not match with the reciprocity filter, i.e., if the first component with the reciprocity filter suggests a match for every entity, then the second component will return no results. In other words, the highest possible recall achievable by the second component is 1 minus the recall of the first component.

Another very important observation comes up from the comparison of the H@1 results shown in the HybEA and HybEA (struct. first) rows of Table 2 and the Recall results (since Precision is always 1.0) shown in the factual first and structural first parts of Table 3, respectively. We notice that the vast majority of matches identified by HybEA come from the reciprocity filter and only a very small number of matches are left to be decided by the ranking of the most likely matches returned by the last component.

Despite the above findings, i.e., that the effectiveness of the reciprocity filter alone (Table 3) is higher when the structural model is executed first, we observe that when put as part of the whole pipeline (Table 2), it is more beneficial to execute the factual model first, in all datasets. This means that the reciprocity filter enables to better train both models, when they have a more balanced contribution.

Removing the structural component.
Similarly, HybEA (w/o struct.) presents the results of our method without the structural component, i.e., it includes the execution of the factual component only, in one cycle. We make the following observations:
Despite the fact that running the factual component first yields better results than the reverse order, yet, running the factual component alone, yields quite low results; worse than running the structural component only. This means that by running the factual component first, we exploit the two components better, compared to running the structural component first. This observation is also supported by the results shown in Table 3, analyzed earlier.

We have confirmed that the reciprocity filter is a reliable way to identify matches with high confidence, as also highlighted in (Efthymiou et al., 2019; Mao et al., 2020). In Table  (Efthymiou et al., 2019; Mao et al., 2020). In Table 3, we showed that most of the matches returned by our method are obtained by this filter, with 100% precision.

In Tables 2 and 3 we have shown that order matters. Despite the fact that the effectiveness of the reciprocity filter alone is higher when the structural component is executed first, in the whole pipeline it is more beneficial to execute the factual component first, in all datasets. Moreover, using the factual component alone yields bad results, compared to employing the structural component alone.

For evaluating the computational cost of HybEA, we report the FLOPS of each component model in Table 4. On one hand, our structural component is much more computationally expensive than our factual component, while being the most effective one according to Table 2. There is thus a clear trade-off here between computational cost and effectiveness. On the other hand, our factual component allows a high gain in effectiveness for a relatively small computational cost.
